WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:05.022
The algorithm is pretty simple in this case.

00:05.804 --> 00:10.094
So this algorithm rests on this traverse procedure.

00:11.157 --> 00:17.010
So we're going to traverse what they call these OR nodes.

00:16.990 --> 00:21.454
So they divide the problem into and nodes and or nodes.

00:21.574 --> 00:28.521
I don't believe that's particularly necessary for us to think about, but here's how this works.

00:28.641 --> 00:31.684
So they traverse the or node s to s prime.

00:32.144 --> 00:44.095
This is simply, again, this is a node, but the node is a path from s to s prime, where we don't know yet what happens in between, right?

00:45.560 --> 00:51.510
So what we'll do is we'll run this procedure select and select it.

00:52.372 --> 01:01.948
You can see it outputs an S prime and the S prime is going to be a node here somewhere in the middle where the model says this is your subdivision point.

01:03.363 --> 01:09.874
and then it will recursively traverse the left and the right branch of this tree.

01:09.934 --> 01:16.586
So it will subdivide the problem into two problems and then recursively call this traverse.

01:16.806 --> 01:19.110
You see that's the function that we're defining.

01:19.090 --> 01:22.074
call this traverse function on these.

01:23.356 --> 01:39.941
So it will subdivide this problem into these problems and for the next step again it will for each of the problems propose a middle node and subdivide it further and so on until you have a full plan.

01:40.281 --> 01:43.005
At some point you're going to have a full plan.

01:42.985 --> 01:47.271
Now, here, again, is the important thing to remember.

01:47.291 --> 01:50.956
This is just one branch of the search.

01:51.016 --> 01:52.898
This is just one possible plan.

01:53.239 --> 01:57.905
And we are going to do a tree search over these plans.

01:58.526 --> 02:08.059
So this select function here, it has returned this s prime, but it could have returned any point between s and s double prime.

02:08.079 --> 02:11.203
So let, in it, this is just one branch.

02:11.183 --> 02:17.490
I'm going to, I don't have space to draw here, but I'm going to draw it down here again.

02:17.510 --> 02:30.325
So it could have also returned this particular node here, like it's a different s' and then subdivided the problem into different problems.

02:31.046 --> 02:37.073
And then of course those problems are now different, so they would be subdivided differently again and so on.

02:37.053 --> 02:45.187
So this top part here is just, if you consider this thing here, your root node, this is where you search from.

02:45.207 --> 02:55.626
This top part is just one node, one branch in the tree, but we could also subdivide like this, and then that would be another branch in your tree.

02:56.066 --> 03:01.035
And this tree here is the thing that you're searching over.

03:01.015 --> 03:04.201
So, it's important to keep this in mind.

03:04.241 --> 03:07.407
We're searching over these different possibilities.

03:08.168 --> 03:14.720
Now, the rest of this algorithm here is basically the carryover from Monte Carlo Tree Search.

03:15.081 --> 03:18.467
And I don't want to go into that in this video.

03:18.447 --> 03:32.584
But if you're interested in how to actually implement this, you'll have to go look at MCTS and then all of this just carries over from that algorithm because you have to keep estimates of value and visit counts in this tree and so on.

03:33.144 --> 03:35.387
And also you have some sort of a value estimator.

03:36.128 --> 03:41.434
But yeah, I'm mainly concerned with how the tree is constructed right here.

03:41.414 --> 03:53.061
So basically, here's the difference between the Monte Carlo tree search and the divide and conquer Monte Carlo.

